"NCBIGene:6608"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SMO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9897934198379517, "span": {"begin": 906, "end": 909}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2736"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GLI2/3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.998513400554657, "span": {"begin": 927, "end": 933}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:51684"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Sufu", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9967002868652344, "span": {"begin": 934, "end": 938}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2735"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GLI", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9969466328620911, "span": {"begin": 998, "end": 1001}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GLI", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.8024053573608398, "span": {"begin": 1055, "end": 1058}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2735"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GLI family", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.995965301990509, "span": {"begin": 1055, "end": 1065}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3508"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GliA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.998046338558197, "span": {"begin": 1106, "end": 1110}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "proteolytically cleaved repressor form", "obj": "RNA", "prob": 0.4832373261451721, "span": {"begin": 1117, "end": 1155}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:11010"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GliR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9984590411186218, "span": {"begin": 1157, "end": 1161}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2737"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Gli3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9986069798469543, "span": {"begin": 1194, "end": 1198}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2735"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Gli1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9990566372871399, "span": {"begin": 1240, "end": 1244}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2736"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Gli2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9988730549812317, "span": {"begin": 1249, "end": 1253}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6608"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SMO", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.994684636592865, "span": {"begin": 1323, "end": 1326}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3508"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GliA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9984140396118164, "span": {"begin": 1377, "end": 1381}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:11010"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "GliR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9969950318336487, "span": {"begin": 1382, "end": 1386}}], "text": "The Glioma-associated onocogene (Gli) family of zinc finger transcription factors (Gli1, Gli2, Gli3) are the primarily downstream effectors of the Hedgehog (HH) signaling cascade. When HH ligand binds to Patched (PTCH), its&rsquo; inhibition on SMO is relieved. SMO this then able to accumulate to the tip of primary cilium in its&rsquo; active form (Corbit, Aanstad et al. 2005, Rohatgi, Milenkovic et al. 2007, Kim, Kato et al. 2009). SMO causes the GLI family to become dislodged from their complex with the negative regulator of HH signaling, Suppressor of Fused (Sufu) (Kogerman, Grimm et al. 1999, Pearse, Collier et al. 1999, Stone, Murone et al. 1999, Tukachinsky, Lopez et al. 2010). The GLI-Sufu complex maintains retention of Gli in the cytosol allowing for exposure to phosphorylation via protein kinase A (PKA) which inhibits downstream signal transduction &nbsp;(Tuson, He et al. 2011). When SMO is activated the GLI2/3-Sufu complex is dismantled allowing for retrograde transport of GLI back into the nucleus (Kim, Kato et al. 2009).   The GLI family is found in both a long activator form (GliA) or a proteolytically cleaved repressor form (GliR). Current understanding is that Gli3 functions primarily as a repressor while Gli1 and Gli2 function mainly as activators of the pathway and that recruitment of SMO to the cilium leads to a increase in the ratio of GliA:GliR (Hui and Angers 2011, Liu 2016).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:56:26 +0000 2026"}